<BaseLayout title="References" description="Bibliography and further reading">
  <article class="references">
    <header class="ref-header">
      <span class="section-label">Bibliography</span>
      <h1>References & Further Reading</h1>
      <p class="ref-subtitle">Sources that informed this portfolio's analysis of manufactured judgment systems</p>
    </header>

    <section class="ref-section">
      <h2>Primary Sources</h2>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Depth Study: Visual Rhetoric of Nuclear Fear</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Lund, Anne.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">"Smiling Sun" Anti-Nuclear Logo.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">1975. Originally created for the Danish anti-nuclear movement (OOA). 36 million items sold 1975-1985, translated into 60+ languages. <a href="https://www.atomkraftnejtak.dk/smilingsun/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">atomkraftnejtak.dk</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">It's Nice That.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">"I'm not a designer, I was just an activist": How The Smiling Sun became one of history's most iconic logos.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">March 8, 2018. Interview with Anne Lund on the logo's design and philosophy. <a href="https://www.itsnicethat.com/features/anne-lund-the-smiling-sun-graphic-design-internationalwomensday-080318" target="_blank" rel="noopener">itsnicethat.com</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Generation Atomic.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">IAEA Atomic Art Contest 2022.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Pro-nuclear advocacy campaign in partnership with IAEA. 90+ submissions from 24 countries. <a href="https://www.generationatomic.org/iaea-art-contest-2022/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">generationatomic.org</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">World Nuclear Association.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Safety of Nuclear Power Reactors.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Statistical analysis of nuclear safety records and comparative energy death rates. <a href="https://world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/safety-of-nuclear-power-reactors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">world-nuclear.org</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Our World in Data.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Death rates from energy production per TWh.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Comparative visualization of mortality rates across energy sources. <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/safest-sources-of-energy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ourworldindata.org</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Gallup.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">40 Years After Three Mile Island, Americans Split on Nuclear Power.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">March 2019. Polling data on nuclear attitudes and the lasting impact of TMI. <a href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/248048/years-three-mile-island-americans-split-nuclear-power.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener">news.gallup.com</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">U.S. Energy Information Administration.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Since the 2011 Fukushima accident, Japan has restarted 14 nuclear reactors.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">2024. Analysis of Japan's post-Fukushima nuclear restart program. <a href="https://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.php?id=64204" target="_blank" rel="noopener">eia.gov</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">World Nuclear Association.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Nuclear Power in France.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Analysis of France's 70% nuclear electricity generation and the 1974 Messmer Plan. <a href="https://world-nuclear.org/information-library/country-profiles/countries-a-f/france" target="_blank" rel="noopener">world-nuclear.org</a></span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Persona Study: The Concerned Parent Archetype</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Women Strike for Peace.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Organizational archives and protest imagery.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">1961-present. Documentation of maternal mobilization against nuclear weapons and energy.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Kahneman, Daniel & Tversky, Amos.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">"Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk."</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Econometrica, 1979. Foundational research on loss aversion in behavioral economics.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Cialdini, Robert.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Influence: The Psychology of Persuasion.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Harper Business, 1984. Analysis of social proof and authority manipulation techniques.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Practice of Embodiment: Algorithmic Judgment</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Washko, Angela.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">The Council on Gender Sensitivity and Behavioral Awareness in World of Warcraft.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">2012-2016. Four-year performance art intervention challenging misogyny in gaming spaces. Recipient of Franklin Furnace Fund Grant 2013-2014. <a href="https://angelawashko.com/section/383766-The-Council-on-Gender-Sensitivity-and-Behavioral-Awareness-in-World-of-Warcraft.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">angelawashko.com</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Reach3 Insights.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">New Research Reveals 59% of Women Surveyed Use a Non-Gendered/Male Identity to Avoid Harassment While Gaming.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">2021. Study on gender masking and harassment avoidance strategies in online gaming. <a href="https://www.reach3insights.com/women-gaming-study" target="_blank" rel="noopener">reach3insights.com</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Crothers, Heather, et al.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">"It's Just Not Safe": Gender-Based Harassment and Toxicity Experiences of Women in Esports.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Games and Culture, 2024. Research finding 76% of female gamers experience gendered harassment. <a href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/15554120241273358" target="_blank" rel="noopener">sagepub.com</a></span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Springer Link.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Sexual Harassment in Valorant and Overwatch Voice Chats.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">2024. Research finding women harassed in every seventh Valorant game; women receive 3x more negative comments than men in voice chat.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Riot Games.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">/dev: Matchmaking in 2024.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Official developer documentation on MMR systems and the natural 50% winrate phenomenon. <a href="https://www.leagueoflegends.com/en-us/news/dev/dev-matchmaking-in-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">leagueoflegends.com</a></span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ref-section">
      <h2>Course Readings & Lectures</h2>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>CT-101: Persuasion and Resistance</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Pater, Ruben.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">CAPS LOCK: How Capitalism Took Hold of Graphic Design, and How to Escape from It.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Valiz, 2021. Analysis of design as activist practice.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Tunstall, Dori.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">"Decolonizing Design Means Putting Indigenous First."</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Course reading on power structures embedded in design practice.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Khan, Nora.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Guest Lecture: Artificial and Real.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">CT-101 Course, Fall 2025. Discussion of simulation, color technology, and "slow seeing."</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Jones, Adrian.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Guest Lecture: The Looking Glass Project.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">CT-101 Course, October 14, 2025. Archival activism and intergenerational storytelling.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ref-section">
      <h2>Further Reading</h2>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Visual Rhetoric & Media Studies</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Sontag, Susan.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Regarding the Pain of Others.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2003. On the ethics and impact of disaster imagery.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Berger, John.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Ways of Seeing.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Penguin, 1972. Foundational text on visual culture and perception.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Algorithmic Systems & Digital Culture</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">O'Neil, Cathy.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Weapons of Math Destruction.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">Crown, 2016. Analysis of algorithmic bias and social harm.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Noble, Safiya Umoja.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Algorithms of Oppression.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">NYU Press, 2018. How search engines reinforce racism.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Eubanks, Virginia.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Automating Inequality.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">St. Martin's Press, 2018. How algorithmic systems target the poor.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ref-category">
        <h3>Gaming & Identity</h3>
        <ul class="ref-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Chess, Shira.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Ready Player Two: Women Gamers and Designed Identity.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">University of Minnesota Press, 2017. On gendered assumptions in game design.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ref-author">Gray, Kishonna L.</span>
            <span class="ref-title">Intersectional Tech: Black Users in Digital Gaming.</span>
            <span class="ref-details">LSU Press, 2020. Race and identity in gaming spaces.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ref-section acknowledgments">
      <h2>Acknowledgments</h2>
      <div class="ack-content">
        <p>This portfolio was created for CT-101: Persuasion and Resistance, taught by Dr. Dorothy R. Santos at UC Santa Cruz, Fall 2025.</p>
        <p>Special thanks to the course TAs for their thoughtful feedback on the Practice of Embodiment assignment, which directly shaped the interactive flowchart's expansion to include bystander intervention paths and deeper engagement with questions of gendered and racial embodiment in gaming.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <nav class="study-nav">
      <a href="/ct101-portfolio/embodiment/" class="nav-prev">
        <span class="nav-label">Previous</span>
        <span class="nav-title">Practice of Embodiment</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/ct101-portfolio/" class="nav-next">
        <span class="nav-label">Back to</span>
        <span class="nav-title">Portfolio Home</span>
      </a>
    </nav>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .references {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 2rem;
  }

  .ref-header {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff10;
  }

  .ref-header h1 {
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .ref-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  /* Sections */
  .ref-section {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  .ref-section h2 {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    display: inline-block;
  }

  /* Categories */
  .ref-category {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .ref-category h3 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  /* Reference List */
  .ref-list {
    list-style: none;
  }

  .ref-list li {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    background: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid #ffffff10;
    border-radius: 8px;
    transition: border-color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .ref-list li:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .ref-author {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }

  .ref-title {
    display: block;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .ref-details {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .ref-details a {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .ref-details a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Acknowledgments */
  .acknowledgments {
    background: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 2rem;
    border: 1px solid #ffffff10;
  }

  .acknowledgments h2 {
    border-bottom: none;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .ack-content p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .ack-content p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* Navigation */
  .study-nav {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    margin-top: 4rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #ffffff10;
  }

  .study-nav a {
    display: block;
    padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
    background: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid #ffffff10;
    border-radius: 8px;
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
  }

  .study-nav a:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .nav-label {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .nav-title {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .nav-next {
    text-align: right;
  }

  /* Responsive */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .study-nav {
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 1rem;
    }

    .nav-next {
      text-align: left;
    }
  }
</style>
